WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:27.400
Good morning. Good morning. Good morning, Chair. Good morning,

2
00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:46.400
Good morning. Thank you for taking the time to join us this morning. We have you in here for 15 minutes, 10 minutes, 10 minutes.

3
00:00:46.399 --> 00:00:59.399
I'd just like to welcome you on behalf of the committee. You've both got personal lived experience through this and put together a very helpful pack for us to consider.

4
00:00:59.399 --> 00:01:07.400
So I'll hand that time over to you now. If you want to leave us any questions, you may, but that's yours. Thank you.

5
00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:20.400
Hello, Maureen, everyone, and thank you for the opportunity to present today. My name is Gerard Rushton, and I'm Chairman of the Meningitis Foundation of Aotearoa, New Zealand.

6
00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:33.400
I had with me today Penny Taylor, a meningitis survivor. We presented to this committee in 2022, at which time we had support from all parties across Parliament.

7
00:01:33.400 --> 00:01:45.400
We also had support from Tafata Ora, Pharmac and the House Select Committee. There has been some progress since then, but our adolescents are still at risk.

8
00:01:45.400 --> 00:01:51.400
So why does meningitis, I'll just ask for the next slide, please.

9
00:01:51.400 --> 00:02:01.400
What is meningitis prevention and awareness matter? The mortality and morbidity rate of meningitis makes it one of the most feared diseases.

10
00:02:01.400 --> 00:02:12.400
It can take a life in a matter of hours, hence the need to protect people with vaccinations, because often treatment comes too late.

11
00:02:12.400 --> 00:02:23.400
The current criteria for adolescence vaccinations means the majority of our at-risk adolescents are simply not protected.

12
00:02:23.400 --> 00:02:34.400
Recent cases in Dunedin in the UK are a stark reminder that without a full and equitable vaccination programme, how quickly an outbreak can grow.

13
00:02:34.400 --> 00:02:40.400
And we believe New Zealand is grossly unprepared to deal with such an outbreak.

14
00:02:40.400 --> 00:02:43.400
Next slide, please.

15
00:02:43.400 --> 00:02:54.400
I'd like now to introduce Penny Taylor. Penny is one of our VIPs, a very impacted person. So thank you Penny, I'd just like to hear your story now.

16
00:02:54.400 --> 00:03:00.400
Sorry, I have a few notes, because my brain does move around a little bit.

17
00:03:00.400 --> 00:03:11.400
So 15 years ago, I contracted meningococcal, and it was a normal typical day.

18
00:03:11.400 --> 00:03:21.400
I was a mum of three and a seven-year-old, and the only symptom I had was vomiting out of all of the symptoms that there are.

19
00:03:21.400 --> 00:03:33.400
I naturally thought it was a bug from my daughter's daycare centre. Within hours, my mum came past my house and found me unconscious.

20
00:03:33.400 --> 00:03:43.400
I was taken to Palmerston Health Hospital, and at that point I was given 30 minutes to live in a 2% survival chance.

21
00:03:44.400 --> 00:03:52.400
So I spent one month in a coma. I blew up twice the size of myself, and all my organs had failed.

22
00:03:52.400 --> 00:04:01.400
And I had a 42 degree temperature, which I was essentially frying from the inside.

23
00:04:01.400 --> 00:04:07.400
As a result, with my organs failing, I then had septicemia come in.

24
00:04:07.400 --> 00:04:19.399
And as you can see by my pictures, it took hold, and I looked like a very severe case of frostbite over my legs and fingers.

25
00:04:19.399 --> 00:04:29.399
After a month, they woke me up, and the Palmerston Health Hospital knew that I would need debriding and skin grafting amputations.

26
00:04:29.399 --> 00:04:35.399
Dialysis is a severe range of internal treatment.

27
00:04:35.400 --> 00:04:43.400
They were trying to get me into Waikato Hospital because the burns and the dialysis is all in the one hospital.

28
00:04:43.400 --> 00:04:46.400
They wouldn't accept me because I was out of the region.

29
00:04:46.400 --> 00:04:56.400
So I was helicoptered to Hutt Hospital for the plastics, and was in their high dependency ward.

30
00:04:56.400 --> 00:05:03.400
At that point, I had my amputation, so I still was at very high risk that I wasn't going to make this surgery.

31
00:05:03.400 --> 00:05:15.400
So after 12 hours, they amputated my legs, they amputated my fingers and my hand, and did all my skin grafting all over my body.

32
00:05:15.400 --> 00:05:20.400
The next month was probably the most tortuous part of the whole journey that needed.

33
00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:24.400
It didn't really need to happen had I gone to Waikato.

34
00:05:24.400 --> 00:05:32.400
Morning and night, I was having surgeries, and in between they were transporting me to Wellington Hospital for dialysis.

35
00:05:32.400 --> 00:05:37.400
So every single bump, touch, I would feel.

36
00:05:37.400 --> 00:05:45.400
The dialysis, although it was working for my kidneys, it would dialyse all the medication, so it left me with nothing to come back on.

37
00:05:45.400 --> 00:05:50.400
And so I was playing catch-up every single day with pain meds.

38
00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:53.400
That was excruciating.

39
00:05:53.400 --> 00:05:58.400
After that, I was transferred back to Palmerston Hospital for rehabilitation.

40
00:05:58.400 --> 00:06:08.400
The hand therapist was on holiday and they had no one else, and as a result, my hand is frozen, and I have limited function in it.

41
00:06:08.400 --> 00:06:15.400
And that is not from the disease, that is from lack of physiotherapy.

42
00:06:15.400 --> 00:06:19.400
As soon as I was out of hospital, everything stopped.

43
00:06:19.400 --> 00:06:27.400
I had no aftercare, I had no physiotherapy, I was there to fight for myself.

44
00:06:27.400 --> 00:06:29.400
I had two small children.

45
00:06:29.400 --> 00:06:32.400
So I was in a wheelchair.

46
00:06:32.400 --> 00:06:37.400
Largely my mum and dad were there to help support me.

47
00:06:37.400 --> 00:06:46.400
But it took me, I had to make a decision to financially, I needed to go back to work because I couldn't survive.

48
00:06:46.400 --> 00:06:53.400
So the only way I could go back, I was to go back part-time because physically I was exhausted.

49
00:06:53.400 --> 00:07:00.400
I was still trying to recover from this disease, run a family and try and have an income.

50
00:07:00.400 --> 00:07:04.400
So it was pretty tough going.

51
00:07:04.400 --> 00:07:09.400
Then came the days of prosthetics.

52
00:07:09.400 --> 00:07:13.400
As you can imagine, my skins were very, very delicate and scarred.

53
00:07:13.400 --> 00:07:21.400
So when I went to the limb centre in Wellington, they literally looked at me and didn't think they could help.

54
00:07:21.400 --> 00:07:32.400
So the five years of working part-time in a five-year battle of prosthetics resulted basically me in a wheelchair.

55
00:07:32.400 --> 00:07:40.400
So completely frustrated by that entire system that prosthetics was my only option, the traditional sockets.

56
00:07:40.400 --> 00:07:49.400
I went searching for something else, which I found a surgeon in Australia who does osteointegration surgery.

57
00:07:49.400 --> 00:07:54.400
And that is an implant that directly goes into your skeleton.

58
00:07:54.400 --> 00:07:58.400
No socket, my skin would be okay.

59
00:07:58.400 --> 00:08:09.400
I qualified for that surgery with my bone density and my internal organs being reasonably healthy.

60
00:08:09.400 --> 00:08:13.400
Once I had that surgery, I had that surgery 10 years ago.

61
00:08:13.400 --> 00:08:24.400
I then went right back to square one to a wheelchair again and I had a two-year rehabilitation program run through the Australian team.

62
00:08:24.400 --> 00:08:32.400
What that surgery has given me back, sorry, on that surgery that was completely unsupported by New Zealand.

63
00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:39.400
They thought I was putting myself at risk and they did not support my decision to have that surgery.

64
00:08:39.399 --> 00:08:47.399
So 10 years of that surgery, I have battled on my own and self-advocated for myself.

65
00:08:47.399 --> 00:08:55.399
But what that surgery has given me, I had to fundraise for the surgery and pay for it myself.

66
00:08:55.399 --> 00:09:00.399
What it has given me, it's enabled me to go back to work full-time.

67
00:09:00.399 --> 00:09:03.399
I am a gym goer.

68
00:09:03.399 --> 00:09:06.399
I walk over 10,000 steps a day.

69
00:09:06.399 --> 00:09:13.399
I do what everyone else does and so that was worth it for me.

70
00:09:13.399 --> 00:09:21.399
I actually got my life back by choosing to fund this myself and make that decision.

71
00:09:21.399 --> 00:09:33.399
I have since worked with the limb centre and with the 10 years of history that I have to present that this could be an option for people.

72
00:09:34.399 --> 00:09:45.399
So this, I guess for me, I have the drive and the motivation to self-advocate and fight through.

73
00:09:45.399 --> 00:09:50.399
I had my two children to live for and that was my driving force.

74
00:09:50.399 --> 00:09:58.399
However, not everyone has that and they don't have a voice, which is a real kicker for me.

75
00:09:58.399 --> 00:10:06.399
The last 15 years has been a complete roller coaster and I have literally done it on my own.

76
00:10:06.399 --> 00:10:11.399
A vaccine could have saved all of that for me.

77
00:10:11.399 --> 00:10:17.399
I was 36 years of age so I was outside of the normal age bracket.

78
00:10:17.399 --> 00:10:24.399
The mental and the physical and the financial impact that has had on me in the last 15 years is significant.

79
00:10:25.399 --> 00:10:34.399
I am evidence of what it does do and the varying conditions that people are left with if they do survive.

80
00:10:34.399 --> 00:10:39.399
Thank you, Penny.

81
00:10:39.399 --> 00:10:41.399
I think you've changed the slide.

82
00:10:41.399 --> 00:10:43.399
Thank you, Penny.

83
00:10:43.399 --> 00:10:45.399
Very brave of you to come here today and share your story.

84
00:10:45.399 --> 00:10:53.399
It's traumatic and I could leave my presentation there because there's justification in its own

85
00:10:53.399 --> 00:10:55.399
for what we're talking about.

86
00:10:55.399 --> 00:11:04.399
Clearly from Penny's presentation, the New Zealand health system is failing us with limited vaccine access,

87
00:11:04.399 --> 00:11:06.399
lack of support for survivors.

88
00:11:06.399 --> 00:11:12.399
We have no fence at the top of the cliff and we have no ambulance at the bottom either.

89
00:11:12.399 --> 00:11:18.399
Since the implementation of the infant vaccination programme in 2023,

90
00:11:18.399 --> 00:11:22.399
the vaccination rates in their infants have raised

91
00:11:22.399 --> 00:11:31.399
and the number of cases of infant meningitis have noticeably reduced.

92
00:11:31.399 --> 00:11:33.399
So the vaccine actually works.

93
00:11:33.399 --> 00:11:38.399
We're concerned the adolescent criteria is far too narrow.

94
00:11:38.399 --> 00:11:39.399
It's confusing.

95
00:11:39.399 --> 00:11:42.399
We question the rationale around it.

96
00:11:42.399 --> 00:11:46.399
Why is it right that someone that can afford to go to boarding school

97
00:11:46.399 --> 00:11:50.399
or be in the halls of residence should qualify for a free vaccination

98
00:11:50.399 --> 00:11:54.399
against anyone else who's an adolescent in our country?

99
00:11:54.399 --> 00:12:00.399
Our Marian Pacifica population of five times more likely to contract meningitis,

100
00:12:00.399 --> 00:12:04.399
yet most of them do not qualify for a free vaccination.

101
00:12:04.399 --> 00:12:06.399
Why?

102
00:12:06.399 --> 00:12:12.399
Meningitis vaccinations applications are penalised in the pharmac process

103
00:12:12.399 --> 00:12:17.399
because simply the more people that require a vaccine

104
00:12:17.399 --> 00:12:19.399
have access to the vaccine,

105
00:12:19.399 --> 00:12:22.399
the more people that need to be vaccinated.

106
00:12:22.399 --> 00:12:24.399
So we're concerned that the vaccination rates

107
00:12:24.399 --> 00:12:27.399
against the inclusion of that vaccine onto the schedule

108
00:12:27.399 --> 00:12:29.399
because of the cost of the implementation.

109
00:12:29.399 --> 00:12:32.399
If New Zealanders want it, we should give it to them.

110
00:12:32.399 --> 00:12:35.399
These inequalities result in deaths and disabilities,

111
00:12:35.399 --> 00:12:37.399
which are preventable.

112
00:12:37.399 --> 00:12:38.399
Just change the slide.

113
00:12:38.399 --> 00:12:40.399
Thank you.

114
00:12:40.399 --> 00:12:42.399
The awareness or lack of it in 2023,

115
00:12:42.399 --> 00:12:45.399
the Health Select Committee report recommended an awareness campaign.

116
00:12:45.399 --> 00:12:49.399
During the period in the absence of a national campaign

117
00:12:49.399 --> 00:12:55.399
from Towharaua, the foundation has led a nationwide awareness campaign.

118
00:12:55.399 --> 00:12:58.399
It has produced and distributed 12,500 colouring in books,

119
00:12:58.399 --> 00:13:00.399
which are in your handout.

120
00:13:00.399 --> 00:13:05.399
It has developed a multilingual symptoms QR code

121
00:13:05.399 --> 00:13:07.399
so that people can download the symptoms

122
00:13:07.399 --> 00:13:11.399
and have it on their phone all the time.

123
00:13:11.399 --> 00:13:14.399
And that improves access to key health information

124
00:13:14.399 --> 00:13:15.399
for them.

125
00:13:15.399 --> 00:13:18.399
We've distributed 8,500 pens and thousands of information brochures

126
00:13:18.399 --> 00:13:21.399
throughout New Zealand universities.

127
00:13:21.399 --> 00:13:23.399
Just to change the slide. Thank you.

128
00:13:23.399 --> 00:13:26.399
The Managitis Foundation has also engaged with universities

129
00:13:26.399 --> 00:13:29.399
across the country via social media.

130
00:13:29.399 --> 00:13:32.399
We've been present at O-Weeks and wellness events

131
00:13:32.399 --> 00:13:35.399
at most universities through New Zealand

132
00:13:35.399 --> 00:13:38.399
and have engaged with thousands of students

133
00:13:38.399 --> 00:13:40.399
during that process.

134
00:13:40.399 --> 00:13:43.399
GSK has driven a television advertising programme

135
00:13:43.399 --> 00:13:46.399
which has raised awareness.

136
00:13:46.399 --> 00:13:50.399
The inconsistent messaging from medical professionals

137
00:13:50.399 --> 00:13:54.399
has evidenced in the feedback from parents of students

138
00:13:54.399 --> 00:13:58.399
and those that provide student accommodation,

139
00:13:58.399 --> 00:14:01.399
which are in your handout, show that there's a complete,

140
00:14:01.399 --> 00:14:04.399
still a lack of awareness around Managitis vaccination

141
00:14:04.399 --> 00:14:06.399
and the need for it.

142
00:14:06.399 --> 00:14:08.399
The underlying theme of all Managitis cases

143
00:14:08.399 --> 00:14:11.399
is simply a lack of awareness.

144
00:14:11.399 --> 00:14:15.399
Te Vata Ora are absent in all of the above.

145
00:14:15.399 --> 00:14:17.399
Next slide, please.

146
00:14:17.399 --> 00:14:19.399
Just to be mindful, we're a few minutes over time.

147
00:14:19.399 --> 00:14:22.399
So our ask is that we need a bipartisan support

148
00:14:22.399 --> 00:14:25.399
for a fully funded vaccination programme.

149
00:14:25.399 --> 00:14:28.399
At minimum, eligibility for the vaccination programme

150
00:14:28.399 --> 00:14:31.399
should be expanded to include all those

151
00:14:31.399 --> 00:14:34.399
who are community services card holders.

152
00:14:34.399 --> 00:14:37.399
We're asking for the support of the Managitis Foundation

153
00:14:37.399 --> 00:14:40.399
for community services card holders.

154
00:14:40.399 --> 00:14:44.399
We're asking for better after care for survivors

155
00:14:44.399 --> 00:14:47.399
and refer to the research document in our handout

156
00:14:47.399 --> 00:14:49.399
from Wellington University in that.

157
00:14:49.399 --> 00:14:52.399
We'd also like improved monitoring

158
00:14:52.399 --> 00:14:55.399
and faster notification of cases.

159
00:14:55.399 --> 00:14:58.399
So we'd welcome any, thank you for your time

160
00:14:58.399 --> 00:15:00.399
and welcome any questions.

161
00:15:00.399 --> 00:15:02.399
Thank you. Thank you, Gerard.

162
00:15:02.399 --> 00:15:04.399
We won't have time for questions, unfortunately,

163
00:15:04.399 --> 00:15:07.399
but we don't necessarily know that we need them.

164
00:15:07.399 --> 00:15:10.399
It's a horrific story, any.

165
00:15:10.399 --> 00:15:14.399
And Gerard, I know from talking previously

166
00:15:14.399 --> 00:15:17.399
what this has done to your family.

167
00:15:17.399 --> 00:15:21.399
Mr Chair, with your permission,

168
00:15:21.399 --> 00:15:25.399
could I be permitted just one very quick question to clarify?

169
00:15:25.399 --> 00:15:26.399
Yes, you may.

170
00:15:26.399 --> 00:15:30.399
Clarify that. Point two of your ask there.

171
00:15:30.399 --> 00:15:33.399
Which age will the community service card

172
00:15:33.399 --> 00:15:36.399
holders be in that proposal?

173
00:15:36.399 --> 00:15:38.399
Our adolescents.

174
00:15:38.399 --> 00:15:41.399
That's the second highest at risk.

175
00:15:41.399 --> 00:15:43.399
Ideally, you want all adolescents

176
00:15:43.399 --> 00:15:45.399
in that minimum community service card?

177
00:15:45.399 --> 00:15:48.399
The best time to implement a vaccination program

178
00:15:48.399 --> 00:15:50.399
is a school-based program

179
00:15:50.399 --> 00:15:53.399
when they're actually, they need to be protected

180
00:15:53.399 --> 00:15:55.399
before they go out into the community.

181
00:15:55.399 --> 00:15:56.399
Thank you.

182
00:15:56.399 --> 00:15:58.399
We thank you for your time.

183
00:15:58.399 --> 00:16:00.399
I mean, you people have the chance to make a difference,

184
00:16:00.399 --> 00:16:02.399
to save lives, to save disabilities,

185
00:16:02.399 --> 00:16:05.399
so we're asking to take that opportunity.

186
00:16:05.399 --> 00:16:07.399
Thank you very much for coming to Wellington today

187
00:16:07.399 --> 00:16:08.399
and presenting to us.

188
00:16:08.399 --> 00:16:12.399
It was a really impactful presentation from you both.

189
00:16:12.399 --> 00:16:13.399
Thank you.

190
00:16:13.399 --> 00:16:14.399
Thank you.
